rdf:Description.NS0:background: The world's largest archipelago, Indonesia achieved independence from the Netherlands in 1949. Current issues include: implementing IMF-mandated reforms of the banking sector, effecting a transition to a popularly elected government after four decades of authoritarianism, addressing charges of cronyism and corruption, holding the military accountable for human rights violations, and resolving growing separatist pressures in Aceh and Irian Jaya. On 30 August 1999 a provincial referendum for independence was overwhelmingly approved by the people of Timor Timur. Concurrence followed by Indonesia's national legislature, and the name East Timor was provisionally adopted. The independent status of East Timor - now under UN administration - has yet to be formally established.
rdf:Description.NS0:location: Southeastern Asia, archipelago between the Indian Ocean and the Pacific Ocean
rdf:Description.NS0:comparativeArea: slightly less than three times the size of Texas
rdf:Description.NS0:climate: tropical; hot, humid; more moderate in highlands
rdf:Description.NS0:terrain: mostly coastal lowlands; larger islands have interior mountains
rdf:Description.NS0:naturalHazard: occasional floods, severe droughts, tsunamis, earthquakes, volcanoes
rdf:Description.NS0:environmentalIssue: water pollution from industrial wastes, sewage
smoke and haze from forest fires
rdf:Description.NS0:literacyDefinition: age 15 and over can read and write
rdf:Description.NS0:formerCountryName: Netherlands East Indies; Dutch East Indies
rdf:Description.NS0:independence: 17 August 1945 (proclaimed independence; on 27 December 1949, Indonesia became legally independent from the Netherlands)
rdf:Description.NS0:constitution: August 1945, abrogated by Federal Constitution of 1949 and Provisional Constitution of 1950, restored 5 July 1959
rdf:Description.NS0:legalSystem: based on Roman-Dutch law, substantially modified by indigenous concepts and by new criminal procedures code; has not accepted compulsory ICJ jurisdiction
rdf:Description.NS0:suffrage: 17 years of age; universal and married persons regardless of age
rdf:Description.NS0:flagDescription: two equal horizontal bands of red (top) and white; similar to the flag of Monaco, which is shorter; also similar to the flag of Poland, which is white (top) and red
rdf:Description.NS0:economyOverview: Indonesia, a vast polyglot nation, faces severe economic problems, stemming from secessionist movements and the low level of security in the regions, the lack of reliable legal recourse in contract disputes, corruption, weaknesses in the banking system, and strained relations with the IMF. Investor confidence will remain low and few new jobs will be created under these circumstances. Growth of 4.8% in 2000 is not sustainable, being attributable to favorable short-term factors, including high world oil prices, a surge in nonoil exports, and increased domestic demand for consumer durables.
rdf:Description.NS0:fiscalYear: calendar year; note - previously was 1 April - 31 March, but starting with 2001, has been changed to calendar year
rdf:Description.NS0:telephoneSystemGeneralAssessment: domestic service fair, international service good
rdf:Description.NS0:telephoneSystemDomestic: interisland microwave system and HF radio police net; domestic satellite communications system
rdf:Description.NS0:telephoneSystemInternational: satellite earth stations - 2 Intelsat (1 Indian Ocean and 1 Pacific Ocean)
rdf:Description.NS0:internationalDispute: Sipadan and Ligitan Islands in dispute with Malaysia
rdf:Description.NS0:illicitDrugs: illicit producer of cannabis largely for domestic use
possible growing role as transshipment point for Golden Triangle heroin
